related.description: Lisa Leslie faces the best frontcourt tandem in the league when L.A. and Sacramento meet in the first round.
related.title: Sparks vs. Monarchs
related.headline: Sparks vs. Monarchs

article.headline: Sacramento takes lead early and coasts
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Monarchs shut down Lisa
Leslie and pushed the top-seeded Los Angeles Sparks to the brink of
elimination from the WNBA playoffs.

Tangela Smith scored 21 points Friday night, helping Sacramento
humble the Sparks 72-52 in the first game of the best-of-three
first-round series.

"They took it to us," said Sparks co-head coach Karleen
Thompson.

The Sparks now have to win Sunday and Tuesday on their home
court to avoid an early exit.

Sacramento's Yolanda Griffith clearly won the battle over Leslie
in the post, getting 17 points and 10 rebounds. Leslie had a career
playoff-low 10 points. Her previous low was 11 points in a lopsided
loss to Houston on Aug. 29, 1999.

Leading by 15 points at intermission, the fourth-seeded Monarchs
used an 11-0 run to build a 26-point lead, 46-20, with 16:32
remaining. Los Angeles never made a serious run.

"They don't have the depth this year like they usually do,"
Smith said. "We go at them aggressive and try to get them tired."

Kara Lawson had 11 points for the Monarchs, who finished the
regular season with three straight victories for an 18-16 record.

Los Angeles has dominated this California rivalry in the
playoffs. The Sparks eliminated the Monarchs in all three previous
playoff series, including last year in the Western Conference
finals. The Sparks lost the first game of that series, too, but
rebounded to beat the Monarchs in the next two games and advance to
the WNBA Finals.

"We won here last year, but then we went there and threw away
Game 2 by not being ready to play," Monarchs coach John Whisenant
said.

"Last year was last year -- it's history," Lisa Leslie said.
"We have to make our own history this year. We sent them home last
year. We'll have to make some adjustments. It's nothing new."

The Sparks never led on Friday, and their high-scoring tandem of
Leslie and Mwadi Mabika shot a combined 9-of-25.

Leslie, a favorite for league MVP this season, was befuddled by
Sacramento's swarming interior defense. She shot 4-of-12 and had
seven rebounds, while Mabika missed from the perimeter until late
in the game, shooting 5-of-13 and finishing with 15 points.

"Offensively, they are the best team in the league," Whisenant
said. "But if we play defense correctly, that's the great
equalizer."

Christi Thomas had 10 points and nine rebounds for Los Angeles.

Smith did most of her damage from the outside. She had eight
quick points to help Sacramento take a 15-4 lead, then kept hitting
the remainder of the game to surpass her previous playoff-high of
17 points.

Smith had 15 points in the first half alone, when the Monarchs
took a 35-20 advantage by the break.

"That's very important for me, getting off to a good start,"
Smith said. "I hit some easy shots to help my confidence. That
opened up things inside for us."

It was a miserable opening half for the Sparks, who shot 8-of-32
and committed nine turnovers. Leslie made 1-of-5 shots and had just
two points.

The Monarchs aren't expecting the same lackluster performance on
Sunday.

"A team like L.A., you know they will come out fighting in Game
2," Lawson said.
